column5: Test.

The visit and talk at the design firm was very inspiring and motivating. It would be great to have more of the speakers who come by to the class directly talk/critique about the project we are working on.
Test.
Test.
The field trip was great, definitely keep this as part of the class!
Test.
It would be fun to have in-class case studies where we are given a problem and must work in teams to develop a successful product design.
It will be interesting to look at how the design concepts are implemented in real world situations by the companies and what the outcomes are.
I would like a little design aesthetics.
Nicer chairs
It would be great if we could get nicer chairs and pizza
It would be great if we could change the classroom to one, where the seating is made in a circular way around the instructor (eg. 150 GSPP) in order to make the interactions more convenient.
It would be great for us to have weekly practice designing, and in class to have discussions about industrial cases to find out other's opinions on design
Given that there are open positions in the class and people on the wait list, it would be nice to see a reallocation of seats.
I like how we are asked to examine the designs of those items that are immediately involved in our daily lives
By making it applicable to industry
more technical and concise material
This class is too long to have everyone sitting down and lectured too. It would be nice if we could break into group discussions or activities to keep us engaged.
We may do this later on, but it would be interesting in addition to smaller group discussions, to engage in group activities/games that relate to these innovative ideas
Explore case studies of how iconic things were designed
Discussion of what type of industrial engineering jobs or companies this course might prepare one for

While this may be a bit unconventional, how about we take like 30 seconds every 30 minutes (or every 60 minutes) to just get up and walk around in circles for a bit, to keep us from falling asleep. The class is interesting, but at the end of the day I'm so tired I can barley keep my head up. I think some movement would really help.
Can we move it to some other lecture hall?
More smaller group discussions
I would appreciate more of an exploration of how various factors and variables are weighted given different situations--the textbook touched on it, I would love some more examples!
Provide more case studies to discuss how different designs imapct the products

Regarding homework: It's cool seeing how other people did their designs for the homework (so far, only HW1), but I'd like to see more formal critique and guidance from the instructor after we turn in the homework i.e. people share their work, then writing on the board the principles/techniques that worked or didn't work for some designs.
Maybe the professor or GSI can show their past work/design for inspiration?
I would love to learn about previous projects done by the professor or GSI.

I think it could be really awesome if through the semester people can talk with everyone else in the class at least one time, sharing it point of view about anything (could be: talk about the last movie you watched). Professor could encourage this spaces. At the end you can have a diverse point of view of around 60 different persons.
Even more discussion-based structure where we get valuable information from the professor but it feels like a conversation.
More discussions and group activities
Have more small group discussions
Going over specific case studies would be useful in the beginning of the course so we can get a better idea of what the course is about.
Break up the class with more activities to keep us moving and engaged. It's a long class and at the end of hump day, no matter how interesting the lecture is, I'm bound to feel tired.
Creativity and thinking out of box is why I want to take this course. So more creative projects would make this course more valuable to me

I think the idea of having anonymous suggestions when having classroom discussions would be very helpful. A lot of times people's ideas can be overshadowed by students who contribute a lot to the class. If there were anonymous suggestions it would be a bit difficult to get cohesive arguments between the peers, but there'd be a stronger variety of suggestions at the onset. In fact, having a section of anonymous suggestions followed by an in-class discussion might be beneficial.
It would be great if we could see more designs and analyze whether they are good or not.

I do not get designing intuitively and my drawing and creativity is a little weak. Can the course content be modified a little to make students who have low design aptitude to be on par with other students?

Homework assignments should be given to groups of twoâ€”each person is paired up with another random student.

This would be a great opportunity to learn how to build and incorporate other's ideas with one's own; it's also a good exercise on how to be adaptable for working in new teams.
I didn't really see the purpose of attending the Campanile event, it didn't seem to relate to the material of the class. Perhaps a better explanation of the relation would be helpful to students.

It could be interesting to do case studies on certain designs of products or systems to discuss and evaluate how effective they are from a human-centered perspective to learn and gain inspiration from designs that already exist.
Have undergrad student assistants similar to the Computer Science department. This allows undergrads to get more value out of the course & to have something to strive for
Bring materials to class for some hands on collaboration and prototyping

I would love to have more in class projects (using simple materials such as construction paper, paper clips, tape, popsicle sticks etc) that can give us a visual learning skill. We should also move around class more and be active!
I think having more group activities would make the class more engaging/exciting. I would like to critique good and bad designs with my classmates so that I can broaden my perspective.
More interactive activities and creative group brainstorming sessions with feedback.

Have a list of suggested design books for different fields (i.e Industrial Design, Web Design, Audio Design, etc.). These could be populated throughout the semester and we could add ones that are suggested by our guest speakers as well as the class.
Some more direction on the project would be useful. I'm not entirely sure what my group is supposed to be doing at this time.

Specific help on how to improve our design. From the projects it seems like some people are significantly more experienced or, in some sense, better. It can be difficult for others to come up to speed.
What about having last 10 mins doing m-cafe in class?
I think a slightly more formalized discussion of homework -- maybe just recording some of the most positive and/or least helpful design attributes various people used.
Homework and other assignments should be more specific about grading/rubric. Even just a little more details about the nature of the assignment (1 page paper, etc.) would be helpful.
Going over current design \news\"/trends/relevant examples from the media at the start of class."
Have discussions every class that involve talking with people you wouldn't normally talk with.

Utilize bCourses more. Streamline communication. Messages/announcements versus emails. Each student has about 5 classes to check for updates and if it is all in one place this makes it easier. The alternative is a student checking email, bcourses, teacher websites & their notes which is more confusing
I really enjoyed the guest lecturer. It would be great to continue to have qualified insightful lecturers like this all semester
It would be nice to receive more immediate feedback on our homework assignments after we submit them. I would like to know what I should improve before completing future assignments.
Field trips
We should do more case studies of successful products. Have more guest speakers to talk about their own experiences with product designs.

Although I am enjoying the engaging aspect of the class, and the very interesting assignments assigned, I am not really sure yet what we will be tested on (for the final) and maybe place more emphasis on topics you believe we should know for the final test.
More instruction on \how to design,\" for example, how to conduct the interviews that shape personas, and methods to synthesize research findings."
Better organization of assignments!
More hands on activity before the speakers so we get more context of where they come from

While the project sounds interesting, my group has no idea where to start. We would appreciate more guidance on how to tackle the project. That being said, the design process you showed us yesterday was also very helpful.

The homework assignments should be more freeform and just more like a creative experience to come up with ideas and explain design choices. Also, can you gives us the timeline of project deliverables and just talk more about the project?
Send out emails earlier in the week, or give full homework instructions during class
Im finding it difficult to determine how I'm doing in the class right now I think a more specific rubric or expectations for our assignments would be helpful

I really enjoy the time we take to share our assignments -- if there were some way to allow people (if they wanted!) to share on a discussion forum, then people who didn't get to present in class would still be able to share their designs.

I feel like all of the online content for this course could be consolidated into just bCourses or just the class website. It would be more convenient for students to have one destination where they can go and receive information.

I could see the website existing for the purposes of advertising the class to outsiders not in the class, which makes sense to me. If this is the case, I would look to make the website more of an informational source, rather than a tool for students.

I am really enjoying the quality of the guest speakers that have come to lectures. It is a little hard to gage how well I am doing in the assignments as everyone's designs are so different, perhaps we could have some way of seeing people's designs, highlighting the better ones, to see what good efforts were. For this same reason I am liking the way Prof. Goldberg gives the whole class feedback on how good the designs that people present in class are.
Faster/more feedback on assignments
It would be nice to receive feedback on our homework. So far we have submitted several assignments but have not received a grade or comments of any sort so I'm not sure what I should be improving.
It would be nice to receive feedback on our homework. So far we have submitted several assignments but have not received a grade or comments of any sort so I'm not sure how to improve.
Streamline communication. Use one method of communication. Its tough for students to check multiple sources & expensive in people time
Please, do it in some other classroom.
Guided brainstorming for group projects!

Homeworks need to be graded quicker for feedback purposes. We're on our 4th assignment and I still don't know how I did on the first three in regards to design decisions, reasoning, personas, criticism, etc.
I liked viewing the homework submissions of other students during class. It would be cool if the homeworks of all of the students (who opt in) is posted somewhere for us to view at our leisure.

While I enjoy the homework, it'd be beneficial to see and discuss (after turning in our homework) how these design problems are solved in industry to get a sense of the design process, the constraints that are faced in a realistic scenario and how research & testing are undertaken.

I think that the importance of a dedicated design notebook hasn't been well communicated. I believe that there are numerous benefits to having a design notebook such as no distractions, its easy to scribble things down, its a place for you to confront problems. I'm not quite sure what it is but scribbling down ideas in another notebook or on your computer is not the same experience as using a design notebook. Part of my strong feelings for having a design notebook stems from the fact that most designs shown off today are final, polished products however I think that this is only one component of design. I think the messier parts, where solutions fail, is just as an important part of the design process. I think having a dedicated space where you can fail and just try things is particularly important to further oneself in design.
At the moment, I have the same suggestions from last week. Very unsure what we will be tested on, however all the assignments definitely makes me think outside of the box
Would we be able to take a tour or class field trip to a design firm or studio?  That would be an awesome way to get an idea of the real world design process.

Can we please break up the large teams into smaller ones? My team is so large we can't even settle on a time to meet before the next class so that we can finish the assignment! I understand you have reasons for limiting the number of teams, but a large team can be somewhat cumbersome and detrimental overall.

More clarity on creativity vs practicality for assignments. It's very different to explore \wouldn't it be crazy if\" type of ideas as opposed to \"this could actually make an improvement\" ideas, and while both have their place, it's unclear which we should focus on for the assignments."

The class does a great job of exposing students to a wide range of fields of design, which all introduce new, interesting perspectives. However, I would also focus more of the dedicated lecture time (not guest speakers) skills required in industrial and user experience design and research. Overall, the class is fantastic!

Receive the grades of the assignments: At this point of the semester I have not received any feedback on how I can improve my design skills. Each class I do my part doing the required assignment, but without feed back I don't know if what I have done is good or bad.
present more projects that are industrial related

Hands on group activities seem to have no sense of direction. I understand the reason behind vague prompts, but there needs to be more guidance/clarity. Take for example, the hands on that was supposed to be focused on the UI of a making a robot out of cardboard. My group was all over the place spitting out crazy ideas of making a robot without even focusing on the prompt that was given (or at least what I think the focus was supposed to be on), which leads to another issue: working in such large groups within small time frames is extremely hard i.e. you guys have 20 min to create a robot UI within your group of 8-10. 

TL;DR: 1) Prompts for hands-ons need to be more emphasized and clarified
2) Logistics during hands-on activities needs to be improved.
3) Prompts for homework are also vague and with no feedback, I have no idea what to even improve on or critically look at. I feel very narrow-minded.
Have feedback/critique on our homework to understand what's working and what's not.

More detailed descriptions of homework/project reports. Our group was exceptionally confused for a long while (and probably still are) about the report because some of us were under the impression that we had to decide on a specific product for our first report.
A better idea of how final grades will work out.
If possible to even have just a vocal note on bcourses for feedback on your assignment as the nature of their grading is so subjective.
Maybe establish who will be taking notes before the lecture
Feedback on what we did well or not so well on the homeworks would be great
Still more feedback on homework assignments in class?  Still unsure of expectations.

The course has been really fun, however, I would like to have more lecture from Prof Goldberg on how to apply the design skills he touches on. While the guest speakers have been great, getting back to the basics to improve our design skills (demonstrated in the homeworks) would be helpful.
I really enjoy developing my design notebook and would love to see what others have written/drawn in their's for inspiration.
Can we get some sort of grading rubric for the homework assignments? I have no idea why I got the grade I did, and while I'm sure it was for the right reason, I have no idea how to improve.

I think evaluation and sharing of other student's homework will help me learn better (more exposure to how others think and increase creativity). It's really interesting how a broad topic for homework can lead to so many different variations of answers. *Mind blown*
More case studies to learn about good and bad designs.
I think it would be beneficial to go over the homework assignments in class more in depth. I like how we look at other people's submissions because it helps me to think more creatively.
A slightly more critical (or specific) analysis of some homework assignments in class so we can see which directions worked and which didn't.
Would it be possible to have a class that focuses on industrial design adhering to some given specifications?
Assignment feedback so we can get some perspective on our ways of thinking
Im with they one who suggest free pizza!!!!
More feedback
Share our homework with each other more often.
we should do group activities so we get to interact with people we don't usually get to meet with.
Assignments are all incredibly vague. A bit more direction would be helpful.
Would like feedback from graders as well as other students.
For the project you want us to use some of the material we've learned in class, but without coming up wit hany specific designs, how can we relate some of these concepts to a children's toy?

I'm not a kind of design guy, and for the grading on the HW creativity is just taking into account when you draw sketches or do something graphic, plain text is no consider creative, even if it has innovative ideas. What can I do to get a good grade in the notebook assignment. Can I do a different project? video? or something else?
While I understand that it's hard to give feedback to 60+ students, even 3 words of feedback on the homework would be helpful. I don't care about the grade, I just want to improve.

Relating class topics back to one another would be useful because we've been told to refer to topics from class in our assignments which can be somewhat difficult since we went over very specific topics.
Punctuate lectures with short discussion activities
Maybe build up to guest lecturer better; seems like we learn something design-related before, and then get a disparate lecture from the guest.

A multi-week personal project with check-ins would be more rewarding than a dozen one-day assignments that are never reviewed

It would be beneficial to iterate based on feedback from the GSI / professor
I think it would be helpful to have sample questions that could be on the final and for the professor to point out specific topics when lecturing that we would need to know for quizzes and the final.
I would like more time to ask the professor or the GSI about the team project.
More specific industry examples, why they failed, why they succeeded.
More industry examples! How they failed, how they succeeded.
Do some more stuff based around our projects
Intergrate more design principles or theories into work. clear expectation of what you want to see implemented in the assignments
Give more in depth descriptions of project/assignment requirements so we know how to best work towards the goal.

I really think we should go over how we could incorporate this material into a job. I know a lot of us may be seniors, and I personally love this material. I think it's really interesting and pertaining to how things work around us, and all I wish is that we could learn about potential jobs that actually apply this. It's a little disheartening to hear all this really cool stuff and use our creativity, then go home only to realize that we don't know where this is offered in the real world.

Please release homework details (including grading criteria) earlier in the week! It is frustrating to have no directions for each homework assignment and complete it, only to have to change it when the grading criteria comes out.

We shouldn't have quizzes (or even a final for that matter). Rather, instead we could have individual projects (that are bigger than homeworks and span multiple weeks) that test what we learned in class. I think design is best learned when applied rather than trying to memorize the ten steps or what that guest lecturer said on that slide. That's not how design is in the real world.

I would like to see groups be mixed up for in class activities, especially for the more casual guest lecturer activities, so that we get the opportunity to work with new people. i see the usefulness with working in our pre-made teams in terms of building a better team dynamic but it would be fun just to switch things up every now and then.

Is there a way homeworks could be shared anonymously to the students so we can all see the work being done? I feel like i class sharing is too limited because some students are just too shy to share, and knowing that my work will be shared somehow will provide some extra motivation for me for each homework.
Provide a crash course on how to make those really pretty homework designs that people have done (e.g. in inDesign or Photoshop, etc.)
Provide a crash course on how to make those really pretty homework poster/designs that people have done (e.g. in inDesign or Photoshop, etc.)

I really enjoyed last class, especially talking with our group members about their homework and finding out their thought processes. I think what can be improved would be somehow linking the guest lectures to our project, like explaining to us how the topics relate to what we're doing. I know the guest speakers provide insight into other domains of design and I enjoy that aspect, but bringing it back full circle to whatever we're doing somehow would be interesting.

It's be interesting to have the class divided in thirds - each hour dedicated to a specific activity/talk. Sometimes, guest talks while very interesting, run long and it's hard to pay attention at 7:30 pm on a Wednesday night.

I really enjoyed the new homework assignment presentation style with a more detailed rubric. At the same time, I feel that we could all learn a lot from viewing each other's homework so I think it would be a good idea to set up a platform to view each other's homework submissions... If this is even possible :)
It would be really interesting to see a dissection of design on UI (i.e mobile app design, etc)

I think it's great that we've been breaking up into groups during class time because it gives us a chance to ask the instructors questions and advice as a group. It would be nice if we could learn more about design principals and philosophies. That said, I've also enjoyed how we've been connecting thing different topics together more lately like sound, ergonomics, and accessibility, which I think is really cool and useful!!

An activity where we could do it individually (say, as homework), and then redo it in pairs or groups to see the different directions to take the assignment and how the ideas generated in a group could be vastly different than those generated individually.
It would be nice to have more class time to work on the project. I really liked how you (Professor Goldberg) spoke to each of the individual groups last time.

I think it would be cool if we were assigned to each do research and write-up a summary on an example of innovative design (perhaps related to industrial design/human factors) in the real world. These could all then be posted somewhere (perhaps online) for everyone to view and learn about.

I think it would be cool if we were assigned to each do research and write-up a summary on an example of innovative design (perhaps related to industrial design/human factors) in the real world. These could all then be posted somewhere (perhaps online) for everyone to view and learn about.

Also, I am a bit confused about the design notebook - what should we be using it for and how much should it have in it? (I seem to remember there being examples online but I can't find them anymore.)

Also, I'd be interested in learning more about intelligent design (beyond the ten steps in the design process). For example, when designing something like a test fixture, even after establishing constraints and whatnot there are still a ton of options in terms of what direction to take the design and I don't really understand how best to evaluate these different options.
Use the bCourses annoucement feature (which sends an email) instead of regular emails
It would be nice if you can give us more example of bad and good industrial design. A good comparison will give a good impression
I would like to see more concrete examples and walk away with a consistent framework to apply to any problem and the a proficiency in the set of tools to do so

I like that we have class notetakers every week; however, it would be more beneficial if we received the notes the week after lecture, rather than have them all at the end of the semester towards the final. That way, we can review the notes during the week, and build on the principles we learned for the following week's class/hw
There are a lot of fake mugs on here. Can we remove all the \this is user X's test comment\" and the \"please take it to another room\". I keep clicking on mugs but they don't have actual content."

The current way note-takers is organized is unnecessarily complicated. Finding each other during breaks and sharing the notes with the GSI is a hassle compared to just having a Google Doc that people input to.

I think the formatting of these text fields could be rewritten to accommodate the longer passages. In other words, this text box could have a minimum height and then if the comment is longer than the box, the box could expand downwards.

It seems strange that we are doing a start-to-finish design project when the lectures places little to no importance on the initial design steps. This class seems to be much more focused on how to enhance an initial design concept/solution by incorporating \human factors.\"

column1: In the future I think students would be better served to work on a handful of 2-3 week projects and case studies improving and critiquing existing designs rather than a full design project."
column5: NULL
I think a lot of the assignments and design notebook aren't super clear. Also posting the notes up on bCourses sooner after the specific lecture would help me review and understand this course.
I love the wide scope of topics we are covering! But I would also enjoy if the principals were further defined!

More engaging assignments that don't necessarily require just paper and pencil. I like the assignment questions that are proposed but the medium in which we present our solutions can be a bit monotonous. Perhaps more visually diverse solutions (not just scanned in paperwork) can generate more creativity in design!
Having more group-involved design project homework.
I feel like there's a disconnect with material we cover in class, and material we're asked to produce in our homeworks/projects.

A little bit of group meeting time during the class would be helpful, given that for most large groups it seems like class is the ONLY time where all of the people in the group are available. I liked the idea of putting us in our project groups to discuss HW assignments because we actually used a bit of the extra time to go over some things for the project.
The technical details we have been covering the past couple of weeks haven't seemed to be very relevant to the goal of the course.  Perhaps more design exercises and fewer equation lectures.
I do not think we should have any more quizzes like the last one. I thought the quiz was too vague and did not really test anything significant

I do not think we should have any more quizzes like the last one. I thought the quiz was vague and did not really test anything significant. Also 15 minutes is not nearly enough time to answer the questions and develop our thoughts
I really enjoyed having the grader's perspective on our homework and how we got to share our work to our groups.

A Toys design class could be really helpful for our projects. Sometimes doing the project report we get stuck wondering which is the next step to design a toy.. It will be really helpful if we can get a guest about this process in advance, so we can work on our project during the semester base on what we learn in that class plus our research.

- no idea what do for the design notebook
- class note taking should be determined before rather than right before class to allow note taker to collaborate together and set up google doc or something beforehand
- class notes should be more of a collaborated effort - we should just all add our notes to a google drive to allow instant access or people who are not the \notetakers\" of the week can still help out (not even sure why we are emailing it to the GSI)

column1: - should have one on one meeting with each team (not just circle the class and talk for 1-2 minutes) but an actual conversation to discuss direction and provide tips
- hw submission should be longer than one page, ie. tell students to upload behance or something to allow them to build portfolio"
column5: NULL
Can we know how many more quizzes will take place? Is this going to be a common thing?
I would like to see the course notes be made easily available on the course website.
I'm having trouble understanding the goal of assignments. It would be nice to have pre-made, detailed assignments being posted a bit earlier.
I like the emails that Ken sends out about weekly assignments and readings, but I wish he would sent them out earlier - like Friday by the latest.
I loved building the robots in class! More hands on design in class would be awesome!
A more defined and direct expectation for assignments and project would be helpful. In addition the real world application would be interesting to discuss.
Have guest lecturers do more hands-on things with us.
More feedback on assignments and get suggestions on how to approach an assignment differently for future assignments
I don't think we should have quizzes, rather Individual projects scattered throughout the semester. This class is intuitive and not theory driven, whicheck is awesome.
When we divide into groups for in-class activities, it would be nice to work with people not in our usual project group.

Relate the guest lectures back to something that we have already learned, or introduce it in a way that incorporates concepts from guest lectures better into the curriculum of the class.  All the guest lectures seem really random to me, and I'm not sure what I am supposed to have learned from each one.

Give us the grading criteria BEFORE assigning a homework or quiz. I have lost so many points in this class because the grading criteria was not clear and I ended up focusing on the wrong things. It feels like my hard work means nothing and as the semester has gone by my motivation for this class has dropped severely because of this.

Really enjoyed last week and this week's lectures on Fitt's Law and usability testing because I see its relevance and importance in design and to our projects, but the guest speaker got way too technical into Fitt's Law and I was lost because it became very research-oriented theoretical. It would've been better if she related more to real-life, practical examples.

Piggybacking on the usability test suggestion, having access to those slides would be extremely helpful as a resource. If you can't give them to us, then even making them just viewable would be awesome!

As someone with very little design experience compared to other students in the class, I still feel a little bit confused on how to catch up. I really am trying to put in the extra time and effort, but I think some extra guidance would be appreciated. I'm not sure exactly what would help just because we have such limited class time, but I think there's only so much we can teach ourselves.

Oftentimes the course material seems irrelevant to the description and some of the guest speakers are speaking too technically that most of the class isn't able to digest the information and apply it to our projects.

While this project is a lot of fun, I really don't see how we can reasonably perform usability testing in such a small amount of time. I'm also not entirely sure we can easily find children in our target audience to perform our user tests. If I were a parent, I would not volunteer my child for a research experiment conducted by a bunch of undergraduate students, mostly due to a lack of credibility.
more group work and interaction with others in the class that aren't on my team

It would be nice to recieve notice of assignments (like the prototype deadline) with more notice. My team found ourselves scrambling to figure out a time we could all meet and figure out how to decide this portion of the project.
homeworks should be biweekly or longer instead of weekly
Assignments seem to be made up arbitrarily and tend to be busy-work, and tend not to be very helpful

I think a lot of my classmates would agree with me when I say there is not enough time to do the prototyping and submit the third report by next Wednesday April 8, that's only 9 days away, especially when many of us are bombarded with midterms.

Would it be possible to push report III back by one week? I think it would be beneficial for all groups since we just got back from spring break. An additional week would allow groups to plan and complete more usability tests and finalize their ideas.

I think a lot of us feel that this upcoming report and usability testing feels a bit rushed, especially since we haven't had any face-to-face contact with our team for a week. If it would be possible to extend these deadlines by a week or so, it would serve all of us to make better prototypes and complete a more thorough report.

I think we should extend the due date for the third report by one week. We all just got back from Spring Break so we will not have much time to do usability tests. Also I would like more time to prototype our idea fully.
I enjoy the guest speakers and think I could get even more out of their presentations if the homework for the week were to correspond with their work and/or what they are presenting on.
More feedback

Since we don't have many weeks of school left, we could have whatever in-class assignments and homework be related to refining our projects in certain aspects. For example, I see on the schedule we have an assignment on responsive homepages for this upcoming week which can be more related to our project.
The team project is interesting to work on but the team size makes meeting and discussion difficult and frustrating. There is always a large distortion in the amount of work each team member does
I really enjoy case examples--like the physiological joint toy (I can't remember the name just now). Discussing these helps me understand how to implement design principles.
I think it would be useful to be given a practice final before dead week so we know what to expect.

the grading for this class is a bit arbitrary sometimes. For some people who do not know how to use a certain software to do homework and make homework look nicer may be in a disadvantage position, because sometimes grade can depend on the presentation.
Maybe tutorials on graphic design? A lot of peoplehave really nice  hw submissions and it would be cool to learn photoshop/other design programs.
I suggest structuring class time so that there are more group activities instead of lectures
Let's build more in class! I really enjoy the challenges that are timed, the liveliness of the class is amazing!
I would like more information on how to conduct user studies and research. It's a bit unclear for me.
I would have liked it if more focus was puton the final project. I feel like the timeline with the progress reports do not push us enough.
More heads-up and details about deliverables
Longer or more frequent stretch breaks.
I really enjoy the class time set aside to work! It allows all of us to do a quick relay of communication.

It is great to learn about how color works. But lets leave that to Physics 7B and 7C. 

It would have been better to go through examples of how colors are used in popular physical designs and logos. eg. why iphone 6 is gold/silver/black and why iphone 5c is in different colors. 

Go more thoroughly through the color designs of well known logos: McDonalds, IBM, apple. Websites, why amazon is of this color, and why facebook is of that color etc. 

Why starbucks logo is green, even though green is not associated with coffee.

[the comment was written during the fascinating video about color cones]

I feel the essence of \design\" often gets lost in the lectures when they become too technical.  For instance, when dealing with color, it would be nice to see successful examples of the ways color was applied in good design and the emotions they generated.  Learning about wavelengths, cones, and rods do not help guide our understanding of color in design.  The focus should be directed more at application and case studies, not theory.  We could also do exercises in using different colors to represent the same objects to figure out what works in those designs and what doesn't.  That could be more useful than memorizing equations."

For future classes, I think peer feedback and reviews are critical because students can help one another grow as designers with new perspectives they wouldn't have thought of on their own. Design critiques are also commonplace in industry I heard, so maybe finding out how professional design teams do this and applying it a classroom setting could be one way to go about designing a peer-peer feedback system!
